# Room Name - TryHackMe: Water Bottle
Date: 16 March 2026
Difficulty: Easy
Category: OSINT / Geolocation

# Scenario
Track down a vanished water station using nothing but fragments of memory and OSINT. The challenge required locating a water refilling station that no longer exists using historical map data and open-source research.

# Tools Used
- Browser
- Google Maps (Street View / Historical Imagery)

# What I Did
- Searched for water refilling stations located along Boni Avenue.
- Opened Google Maps Street View for Boni Avenue and used the historical imagery feature to go back to 2014.
- Identified a water refilling station visible in the 2014 street view: Aquabest
- Searched for Aquabest's contact information and found their phone number on a contact page: +639228721228
- Constructed the flag following the given format (Water Station name in lowercase + _ + Contact Number): THM{aquabest_639228721228}

# What I Found
- Location: Boni Avenue
- Water Station Name: Aquabest
- Contact Number: +639228721228
- Flag: THM{aquabest_639228721228}

# Key Learning
Google Maps Street View retains historical imagery going back several years, making it a powerful tool for reconstructing past physical environments. Businesses that have since closed or moved can still be identified through archived street-level photography. Combining geolocation with historical imagery is a core OSINT technique for tracking entities that no longer have an active online presence.

# What I Would Flag in a Real SOC
- Historical map data is publicly accessible and can be used by adversaries to reconstruct past physical security layouts, entry points, or facility configurations that have since changed
- Business contact information persisted on old websites or cached pages remains searchable long after a business closes, contributing to a persistent digital footprint
- OSINT investigators and threat actors alike can use Street View timelines to verify or disprove alibis, track physical movements, or identify past associates of a target location
